
  <sn><md>### Difference between Bulk Density and Particle Density

| **Bulk Density**                                                                 | **Particle Density**                                                 |
| -------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Defined as the `mass of soil solid` per unit volume of `total soil`.             | Defined as the `mass of soil solid` per unit volume of `soil solid`. |
| **Ms = Mass of soil solid**; **Vt = Volume of total soil**                       | **Ms = Mass of soil solid**; **Vs = Volume of soil solid**           |
| Fine-textured soils: **1.1–1.3 g/cm³**; Coarse-textured soils: **1.4–1.8 g/cm³** | Normal soils ≈ **2.65 g/cm³**                                        |
| `Value varies` with **pore volume** of the soil.                                   | `Value is specific` for a given soil.                              |
| Determined by `core method`.                                                   | Determined by `pycnometer method`.                                 |
| Influenced by **texture, organic matter, cultivation practices**, etc.           | Dependent on **chemical and mineral composition**.                   |
| High bulk density indicates `soil compactness`.                                | Has `no relation` to compactness.                                  |
| Also called `apparent density`.                                                | Also called `true` or `absolute density`.                        |
</md></sn>
