<sn><md>### Difference between Mass Flow and Diffusion

| **Mass Flow**                                                                                  | **Diffusion**                                         |
| ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------- |
| Movement of a body along with its masses.                                                      | Molecular transfer of gases through porous media.     |
| Occurs due to `difference in total pressure`.                                                | Occurs due to a `concentration gradient`.           |
| `Less important` than diffusion in total exchange of gases between soil air and atmospheric air. | Most gaseous interchange in soil occurs by diffusion. |
</md></sn><sn><md>### Difference between Mass Wetness and Volume Wetness

| **Mass Wetness**                                                 | **Volume Wetness**                                                                        |
| ---------------------------------------------------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Defined as the mass of water relative to the mass of soil solid. | Defined as the volume of water relative to the total volume of soil.                      |
| $w = M_w / M_s$                                                |                                                                                           |
| Where: $M_w$ Mass of water, $M_s =$ Mass of soil solid     | $\theta = V_w / V_t$                                                                    |
| Where: $V_w =$ Volume of water, $V_t =$ Total soil volume    |                                                                                           |
| Mass wetness ranges from `25–60%` in different soils.          | Sandy soils ≈ `40%`, medium-textured ≈ `50%`, clayey soils ≈ `60%` (at saturation). |
| `Less convenient` than volume wetness.                             | `More convenient` than mass wetness.                                                        |
</md></sn><sn><md>### Difference between Soil Texture and Soil Structure

| **Soil Texture**                                      | **Soil Structure**                                         |
| ----------------------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------------- |
| `Relative proportion of` sand, silt and clay particles. | `Arrangement of` sand, silt and clay into aggregates.        |
| Can`not` be `modified` easily.                            | Can `be modified` by management.                             |
| `Affects` soil structure.                               | Does `not affect` soil texture.                              |
| A soil must have texture.                             | A soil may be structureless.                               |
| Depends mostly on rocks and weathering.               | Depends on cohesion, adhesion, climate, and other factors. |</md></sn><sn><md>### Difference between Cohesion and Adhesion

| **Cohesion**                                            | **Adhesion**                                                  |
| ------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Force of attraction between `similar molecules`.      | Force of attraction between `dissimilar substances`.        |
| Causes `surface tension`, meniscus, and capillary action. | Causes capillary action and meniscus formation in containers. |
| Strong cohesion `forms water droplets` on surfaces.       | Strong adhesion helps `liquid spread` on surfaces.              |
| Includes `Van der Waals` forces and `hydrogen` bonding.     | Includes `electrostatic` or `mechanical` forces.                  |</md></sn>